Each layer has clearly defined responsibilities and communicates with
adjacent layers through well-defined interfaces.

@node Backend Structure
@section Backend Structure

The backend is organized as a collection of Zig source modules, each
responsible for a specific area of functionality.

@table @asis
@item main.zig
The application entry point.  This module initializes configuration,
sets up the database, registers routes, and starts the HTTP server.

@item http.zig
The HTTP server implementation.  This module handles TCP connections,
parses HTTP requests, and manages routing.

@item config.zig
Configuration management.  Reads environment variables and provides
typed access to configuration values throughout the application.

@item db.zig
Database abstraction.  Manages the SQLite connection, executes queries,
and handles schema migrations.

@item auth.zig
Authentication logic.  Handles user registration, login, logout, and
session management.

@item security.zig
Security-related functionality.  Exports security utilities from other
modules for convenience.

@item password.zig
Password hashing using Argon2id.  Provides secure password hashing and
verification, while still recognizing legacy hashes for migration.

@item tokens.zig
JWT token generation and validation.  Creates signed tokens containing
user session information.

@item payments.zig
Monero payment support.  Handles exchange-rate lookups, invoice
creation, and payment status checks.

@item llm.zig
Per-user LLM provider configuration and chat endpoints.

@item media.zig
Media upload and static file serving.

@item ratelimit.zig
Rate limiting implementation.  Tracks request counts per IP address
and enforces configurable limits.

@item validation.zig
Input validation and sanitization.  Validates user input according to
defined rules and sanitizes data to prevent injection attacks.

@item audit.zig
Security audit logging.  Records security-relevant events such as
login attempts and administrative actions.

@item posts.zig, users.zig, timeline.zig, etc.
Domain-specific route handlers for posts, users, timeline, and other
application features.
@end table

@node HTTP Server
@section HTTP Server

The HTTP server is implemented from scratch in Zig rather than using an
existing framework.  This provides several advantages:

@itemize @bullet
@item
No external dependencies beyond the Zig standard library.

@item
Small binary size, suitable for constrained environments.

@item
Full control over request handling semantics.
@end itemize

The server supports several categories of routes:

@table @asis
@item Public routes
Accessible without authentication.  These include health checks and
public profile data.

@item Protected routes
Require a valid @code{auth_token} cookie or bearer token.  The server
validates the JWT token before invoking the handler.

@item Parameterized routes
Include variable segments such as @code{:id} or @code{:username}.
The server extracts these values and passes them to handlers.
@end table

@node Database Layer
@section Database Layer

The database layer abstracts SQLite operations behind a simple interface.
It handles connection management, query execution, and schema
migrations.

SQLite was chosen for its simplicity and zero-configuration operation.
The database file is stored on disk and can be backed up using
standard file tools.  Migrations are applied automatically on startup.

@node Frontend Structure
@section Frontend Structure

The frontend is a React single-page application built with Vite.  It is
organized into several directories:

@table @asis
@item src/components/
Reusable user interface components.  The @file{ui/} subdirectory
contains primitive components from Radix UI.

@item src/pages/
Route components that correspond to application pages.  Each page
handles a specific URL path.

@item src/context/
React context providers for global state, particularly authentication
state.

@item src/api.ts
The centralized API client that handles all communication with the
backend.

@item src/types.ts
TypeScript type definitions for API requests and responses.
@end table

State management uses React's built-in mechanisms: @code{useState}
for local component state, context providers for shared state, and
React Router for navigation state.

@node Data Flow
@section Data Flow

Understanding how requests flow through the system is helpful when
debugging or extending Xeetapus.

@subheading Request Processing Pipeline

When a client makes a request, it passes through several stages:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{Rate limiting.}  The server checks whether the client's IP
address has exceeded the rate limit.  If so, a @code{429 Too Many
Requests} response is returned.

@item
@strong{CORS validation.}  The server checks whether the request's
origin is in the allowed list.  If not, a @code{403 Forbidden}
response is returned.

@item
@strong{Route matching.}  The server attempts to match the request path
to a registered route.  If no route matches, a @code{404 Not Found}
response is returned.

@item
@strong{Authentication.}  For protected routes, the server extracts the
auth token from the cookie or Authorization header and validates the
JWT token.  If the token is invalid or missing, a @code{401 Unauthorized}
response is returned.

@item
@strong{CSRF verification.}  For state-changing requests (POST, PUT,
DELETE), the server validates the CSRF token.  If the token is invalid,
a @code{403 Forbidden} response is returned.

@item
@strong{Input validation.}  Request body parameters are validated
according to the route's rules.  Invalid input results in a
@code{400 Bad Request} response.

@item
@strong{Route handler.}  If all preceding checks pass, the request
reaches the route handler, which executes the business logic and
generates a response.

@item
@strong{Security headers.}  Before sending the response, the server
adds security-related HTTP headers such as @code{X-Frame-Options} and
@code{Content-Security-Policy}.
@end enumerate

@subheading Authentication Flow

When a user logs in, the following sequence occurs:

@enumerate
@item
The client sends a POST request to @code{/api/auth/login} with the
username and password.

@item
The server validates the credentials against the stored password hash.

@item
On success, the server generates a JWT token containing the user's ID.

@item
The server sets an @code{auth_token} cookie containing the JWT token
and returns the user's profile plus a CSRF token.

@item
On subsequent requests, the browser automatically includes the
auth_token cookie.

@item
The server extracts and validates the JWT from the cookie.
@end enumerate

@node Security Architecture
@section Security Architecture

Security is implemented as a series of independent layers, each
addressing a specific threat.  This defense-in-depth approach ensures
that a failure in one layer does not compromise the entire system.

For detailed information about security features, see @ref{Security
Implementation}.

The main security components are:

@table @asis
@item Password hashing
Passwords are hashed using Argon2id with configurable time, memory, and
parallelism parameters.  The backend still recognizes legacy PBKDF2 and
SHA-256 hashes during migration.

@item JWT tokens
Authentication tokens are signed using HMAC-SHA256.  The server verifies
the signature and expiration before trusting the token contents.

@item CSRF protection
State-changing requests require a valid CSRF token in the
@code{X-CSRF-Token} header.  Tokens are signed and expire after 24
hours.

@item Rate limiting
IP-based rate limiting prevents brute force attacks and denial of
service.  The sliding window algorithm provides fair throttling.

@item Input validation
All user input is validated before use.  This prevents injection attacks
and ensures data integrity.
@end table

@node Performance Considerations
@section Performance Considerations

Xeetapus is designed for simplicity and correctness rather than
maximum performance.  Nevertheless, several measures ensure reasonable
responsiveness.

@subheading Backend Optimizations

The backend uses several performance techniques:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Single database connection with efficient query patterns avoids
connection overhead.

@item
Arena allocators reduce memory allocation frequency during request
handling.

@item
Static files are served from memory when possible, reducing disk I/O.

@item
SQLite with appropriate indexes handles typical workloads efficiently.
@end itemize

@subheading Frontend Optimizations

The frontend build process includes several optimizations:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Code splitting separates vendor libraries (React, React DOM) from
application code, improving caching efficiency.

@item
Vite's development server provides fast module replacement during
development.

@item
Tailwind CSS removes unused styles, reducing CSS bundle size.
@end itemize

@subheading Scalability Limitations

The current architecture has some limitations for large-scale
deployments:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Single-process backend cannot utilize multiple CPU cores without
additional configuration.

@item
SQLite uses a file-based locking model that limits concurrent write
throughput.

@item
No built-in caching layer means repeated database queries are not
memoized.
@end itemize

For high-traffic deployments, consider running multiple backend
instances behind a load balancer, migrating to PostgreSQL, or adding a
caching layer such as Redis.

@node Design Rationale
@section Design Rationale

This section explains why certain technical decisions were made.

@subsection Why Zig for the Backend?

Zig was chosen for several reasons:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Performance comparable to C, important for a server handling many
concurrent connections.

@item
Memory safety without garbage collection, reducing latency spikes.

@item
Single binary deployment, simplifying operations.

@item
Direct SQLite bindings through a simple C interop mechanism.
@end itemize

@subsection Why SQLite?

SQLite provides several advantages for a project like Xeetapus:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Zero-configuration operation.  No database server to install or manage.

@item
Single-file database makes backups trivial.

@item
Sufficient performance for moderate traffic levels.

@item
Easy migration to PostgreSQL if needed later.
@end itemize

@subsection Why React?

React is a mature, widely-used framework with excellent tooling:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Large ecosystem of libraries and components.

@item
Strong TypeScript integration catches errors at compile time.

@item
Vite provides an excellent development experience with fast hot module
replacement.

@item
Wide availability of developers familiar with the framework.
@end itemize

